I'd like to look back

00:56:00.373 --> 00:56:02.094
to the past again if you don't mind.

00:56:02.150 --> 00:56:08.612
So you mentioned that herding agriculture
is a relatively recent invention, and has

00:56:08.637 --> 00:56:12.857
a lot of not very positive effects on
human health, and welfare, and so forth.

00:56:13.701 --> 00:56:17.465
There are actually a number
of anthropologists who have looked at

00:56:17.793 --> 00:56:20.753
agricultural more generally,
like Jared Diamond, and so forth.

00:56:20.981 --> 00:56:23.792
And basically, concluded
that it was a terrible idea.

00:56:24.019 --> 00:56:28.501
That not just animals, but agriculture
in general, cereal grains and so forth.

00:56:29.126 --> 00:56:33.829
I'm just wondering what your feeling is
about that, the general aspect

00:56:34.306 --> 00:56:37.993
of pre-agricultural versus
post-agricultural health

00:56:38.082 --> 00:56:39.570
not just looking at animals.

00:56:39.694 --> 00:56:41.696
WILL TUTTLE: Yeah.
That's a great question.

00:56:41.721 --> 00:56:44.619
Basically, these people
that are writing this,

00:56:45.088 --> 00:56:47.458
I don't think they have
The World Peace Diet view.

00:56:48.421 --> 00:56:50.784
They're meat eaters.
Jared Diamond's a meat eater.

00:56:50.880 --> 00:56:54.304
And so there's a tendency to look at
things from that perspective of,

00:56:54.535 --> 00:56:56.869
we're meat eaters
and this is how we see it.

00:56:57.066 --> 00:57:02.443
And to sort of say all agriculture is
sort of bad. It's unnatural.

00:57:02.643 --> 00:57:07.753
We should go back kind of to living
just gathering like people did.

00:57:08.171 --> 00:57:12.689
But I think, basically,
there's two kinds of agriculture.

00:57:12.714 --> 00:57:13.842
They're very different.

00:57:13.867 --> 00:57:16.695
And we have a tendency to just--
someone says, I'm a farmer.

00:57:16.745 --> 00:57:19.381
Oh, you're a farmer.
What kind of a farmer?

00:57:19.569 --> 00:57:23.034
Because there's plant agriculture's
and there's animal agriculture.

00:57:23.354 --> 00:57:27.007
And from the very beginning, plant
agriculture was essentially women's work.

00:57:27.658 --> 00:57:31.972
And it was work that was working
essentially with nature.

00:57:32.285 --> 00:57:36.056
I mean, you plant something
and this miracle happens.

00:57:36.222 --> 00:57:39.004
You plant one seed
and a thousand seeds come.

00:57:39.029 --> 00:57:41.488
And then you plant one of those
and a thousand more.

00:57:41.560 --> 00:57:45.118
Working with the abundance of nature.
You're working with cycles of nature.

00:57:45.752 --> 00:57:50.818
And with the essential abundance
and fertility of nature.

00:57:51.410 --> 00:57:55.600
Whereas, with animal agriculture,
was essentially men's work.

00:57:55.852 --> 00:57:59.414
And the animals were always fighting back.
They were always resisting.

00:57:59.439 --> 00:58:02.278
They did not want to be killed,
to have their babies stolen.

00:58:02.303 --> 00:58:05.361
They did not want to be raped
and impregnated against their will.

00:58:05.645 --> 00:58:07.411
So men had to violate them.

00:58:07.568 --> 00:58:09.667
They had to hit them.
They had to rape them.

00:58:09.692 --> 00:58:13.591
They had to hold them down
and brand them, just incredible violence.

00:58:14.097 --> 00:58:18.626
And so we created a culture
mainly of meat-eating where the grains--

00:58:18.879 --> 00:58:22.441
we're feeding the grains to these animals.

00:58:22.658 --> 00:58:27.683
But all of us know, if we were to go--
anyone who goes into a well-tended

00:58:27.912 --> 00:58:31.346
and loved garden of vegetables,
it's a wonderful place to be.

00:58:31.415 --> 00:58:34.588
It's beautiful. There's biodiversity.
There's life happening there.

00:58:34.613 --> 00:58:38.012
Any one of us went into a slaughterhouse,
it's like, let me out of here.

00:58:38.037 --> 00:58:41.371
It's a horrible, terrible thing.
So I think we have to realize

00:58:41.520 --> 00:58:44.493
that these are fundamentally
different ways of agriculture.

00:58:45.034 --> 00:58:48.444
And I think that we are here, personally,

00:58:48.591 --> 00:58:51.493
to work in harmony with nature,
to create gardens.

00:58:51.691 --> 00:58:55.569
And the new forms of gardening
that are developing-- veganic gardening

00:58:55.776 --> 00:58:58.910
where we use no animal inputs at all,
food forests, which--

00:58:59.058 --> 00:59:01.965
there's some people in Canada,
we were just visiting them,

00:59:01.990 --> 00:59:04.516
and other places that are building
these food forests

00:59:04.811 --> 00:59:06.901
where you're growing huge amounts of food.

00:59:06.926 --> 00:59:09.323
And it doesn't even look like
it's anything there.

00:59:09.348 --> 00:59:13.245
They have fruit trees and then
other vegetables, and flowers,

00:59:13.284 --> 00:59:16.356
and things just all going together
and creating these ecosystems.

00:59:16.381 --> 00:59:19.305
As we understand these things
more and more, we realize

00:59:19.330 --> 00:59:22.490
we can grow enough food to feed everyone
on a fraction of the land.

00:59:22.515 --> 00:59:26.000
If people ate a plant-based diet,
we could have forests coming back,

00:59:26.025 --> 00:59:30.081
the rainforests coming back, the oceans
coming back. We wouldn't need to kill fish

00:59:30.410 --> 00:59:33.843
Cows, for example, are eating more fish
in the US than human beings are

00:59:33.868 --> 00:59:37.158
because we're feeding the fish
to the cows, so they'll give more milk.

00:59:37.595 --> 00:59:40.670
And it's an incredibly violent,
devastating project.

00:59:40.837 --> 00:59:44.046
And we're doing plant agriculture the way
we do animal agriculture.

00:59:44.071 --> 00:59:46.652
Since we're an animal agriculture
society essentially,

00:59:47.424 --> 00:59:51.480
 we do plant agriculture
with monocropping and violence,

00:59:51.514 --> 00:59:54.369
with all these chemicals,
and herbicides, and fungicides.

00:59:54.496 --> 00:59:57.401
It's a war against nature.
We're killing everything else.

00:59:57.448 --> 01:00:00.963
We don't want any other animals.
Any black birds, we try to kill them off.

01:00:00.988 --> 01:00:05.143
So we're looking with the lens
of animal agriculture at all agriculture.

01:00:05.264 --> 01:00:07.720
And you're right. I mean, he's right.
It's terrible.

01:00:07.745 --> 01:00:12.621
But that's because we did animal culture.
We didn't do plant agriculture properly.

01:00:12.772 --> 01:00:15.989
And I think we have the chance to do that.
But much love to you all.

